<DOC><DOCNO> AP890601-0176 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1608EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Spain-Strikes     06-01 0242</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Spain-Strikes,0248</SECOND><HEAD>Strikes Black Out TV; Threaten to Disrupt Trains</HEAD><DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Workers at the state-run Spanish televisionbegan a 24-hour strike for better pay Thursday, cancellingprogramming for only the second time since broadcasting began in1956.   Thousands of rail passengers, meanwhile, braced for a one-daystrike Friday at the state-controlled rail system as its 63,000employees continued a long-running battle with management forbetter pay.   The strikes formed part of a six-month battle for higher pay byemployees of state enterprises who oppose the Socialistadministration's efforts to keep pay increases moderate to containinflation that is running at a 6.7 percent annually.   A rail spokeswoman guaranteed service on four internationalroutes _ Madrid-Paris, Barcelona-Paris, Barcelona-Bern,Switzerland, and Barcelona-Geneva _ as well as 19 night trains toand from major provincial capitals.   On Friday, between 50 percent and 75 percent of regular commutertrains would be in service and only during rush hours, the railwaysaid.   Television union official Joaquin Aguilar said Thursday the onlybroadcasts would be four, 20-minute news segments, followed byobligatory public service campaign spots for the June 15 Europeanparliamentary elections and an hour of children's cartoons.   The only previous 24-hour TV strike in Spain came Dec. 14, whenSocialist and Communist unions carried out a general strike topressure the government of Socialist Prime Minister to make aleftward shift away from inflation-fighting economic austeritypolicies to greatly increase social spending.</TEXT></DOC>